\subsection{\href{https://beta.lmfdb.org/knowledge/show/lf.slope_content}{Slope content of an extension of $p$-adic fields}}
\begin{definition*}\label{lf.slope_content}
\uses{lf.galois_invariants,lf.inertia_group,lf.padic_field,lf.residue_field,lf.tame_degree,lf.unramified_degree,lf.unramified_subfield,nf.galois_closure,nf.galois_group}
Let $L/K$ be an extension of \hyperref[lf.padic_field]{$p$-adic fields}.
Let $G$ be the \hyperref[nf.galois_group]{Galois group} of the 
\hyperref[nf.galois_closure]{Galois closure}
$L^{gal}/K$ of $L/K$.  Then $G$ has a filtration by \hyperref[lf.galois_invariants]{higher ramification groups}, which in turn are connected to the discriminants of subfields of $L^{gal}$.  The *slope content* encodes information about this filtration giving the location and sizes of the jumps.

Let $G^i$ be the $i$th higher ramification group in upper numbering from Serre's <i>Local Fields</i> \cite{doi:10.1007/978-1-4757-5673-9}, Chapter IV.  They form a descending filtration of normal subgroups where $i$ is a continuous parameter, $i\geq -1$.  Let $G^{(j)} = G^{j-1}$, and $G^{(j+)} = \cup_{\epsilon>0} G^{(j+\epsilon)}$.  Then

\begin{itemize}
\item  $G^{(0)}=G$.
\end{itemize}

\begin{itemize}
\item  $G^{(1)}$ is the \hyperref[lf.inertia_group]{inertia subgroup} of $G$, i.e., the kernel of the natural map from $G$ to the Galois group of the \hyperref[lf.residue_field]{residue field}.
\end{itemize}

\begin{itemize}
\item  the fixed field of $G^{(1)}$ is the maximum \hyperref[lf.unramified_subfield]{unramified subfield} of $L^{gal}/K$, which we denote by $L^{un}$.  The degree $[L^{un}:K]$ is the \hyperref[lf.unramified_degree]{unramified degree} for $L^{gal}/K$.  The extension $L^{gal}/L^{un}$ is totally ramified.
\end{itemize}

\begin{itemize}
\item  the group $G^{(1)}/G^{(1+)}$ is cyclic of order prime to $p$.  Its order is the \hyperref[lf.tame_degree]{tame degree} for $L^{gal}/K$ as it is the degree of the largest tamely totally ramified subextension.  
\end{itemize}

\begin{itemize}
\item  The group $G^{(1+)}$ is a $p$-group.  Values of $s>1$ giving jumps in the filtration $G^{(s)}\neq G^{(s+)}$ are \textbf{wild Artin slopes}.  We repeat a slope $m$ times if $p^m =[G^{(s)} : G^{(s+)}]$, and then list the wild slopes in non-decreasing order.
\end{itemize}

The \textbf{Artin slope content} then takes the form $[s_1,\ldots, s_k]_t^u$ where $t$ is the tame degree, $u$ is the degree of the maximum unramified subfield, and the $s_i$ give the list of the wild slopes.  In particular, $[L^{gal}:K]=tup^k$.  If $t$ or $u$ is equal to $1$, it is not printed.

The \textbf{Swan slopes} are obtained from the Artin slopes by subtracting 1.
\end{definition*}


